      <h1>Technical Analysis for Fundamental Investors</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">A skeptical guide to what actually works (and what to ignore) when timing your entries and exits.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <p>If you identify as a fundamental or value investor, you likely view Technical Analysis (TA) with healthy skepticism. Reading tea leaves, drawing arbitrary lines on charts, and predicting the future based on past squiggles goes against the core philosophy of buying fractional ownership in real businesses.</p>
      <p><strong>However, ignoring price action entirely is a mistake.</strong></p>
      <p>While fundamentals dictate <em>what</em> you should buy, simple technical analysis can significantly improve <em>when</em> you buy it. This guide cuts through the noise to highlight the few technical concepts that actually possess empirical backing and practical utility for long-term investors.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Why Fundamental Investors Should Care</h2>
    <p>Value investors often fall into the "value trap" — buying a statistically cheap stock only to watch it get much cheaper. This happens because the market knows something the balance sheet doesn't reflect yet, or simply because institutional momentum is aggressively against the stock.</p>
    <p>Using basic technical filters acts as a risk management tool. It prevents you from catching falling knives and helps you optimize your entry points. You don't need to become a day trader; you just need to understand where the herd is moving and where major capital is stationed.</p>

    <h2>Support & Resistance: Psychology, Not Magic</h2>
    <p>Support and resistance levels are perhaps the most reliable concepts in technical analysis. They aren't magical forcefields; they are visual representations of market psychology, memory, and supply/demand dynamics.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Support:</strong> A price level where a stock has historically had difficulty falling below. Why? Because buyers who missed out last time are waiting to buy, and short sellers are covering their positions to take profits.</li>
      <li><strong>Resistance:</strong> A price level where selling pressure overcomes buying pressure. This often represents the "breakeven" point for investors who bought at a previous peak and are desperate to get their money back.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>How to use it:</strong> If your DCF model says a stock is worth $100, and it's currently at $80, look at the chart. If there's massive historical support at $75, you might stagger your entry or wait to see if it tests that $75 level before deploying your full position.
    </div>

    <h2>Moving Averages: The Institutional Trend Filters</h2>
    <p>Moving averages smooth out price data to reveal the underlying trend. The two most important are the 50-day and 200-day Simple Moving Averages (SMA).</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>50-Day SMA:</strong> The medium-term trend line. Institutional algorithms often use this level to accumulate or distribute shares.</li>
      <li><strong>200-Day SMA:</strong> The ultimate long-term trend filter. Paul Tudor Jones famously noted that nothing good happens below the 200-day moving average.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>The Crossover Visualizer</h3>
    <p>When a shorter-term moving average crosses a longer-term one, it signals a potential shift in momentum. The "Golden Cross" (50-day crossing above the 200-day) is a bullish signal, while the "Death Cross" (50-day crossing below) is bearish.</p>

