    <h2>Volume: The One Indicator You Must Watch</h2>
    <p>Price moves can be manipulated in low liquidity, but volume reveals the truth. Volume is the footprint of institutional money. Retail investors cannot move a multi-billion dollar stock on their own.</p>
    <p>If a stock breaks out to a new high on weak volume, it's highly suspect. If it crashes through support on massive volume, the fundamental story has likely changed, even if you haven't read the news yet.</p>

    <h2>RSI: A Timing Tool for Stocks You Already Want</h2>
    <p>The Relative Strength Index (RSI) measures the speed and change of price movements on a scale of 0 to 100.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Over 70:</strong> Considered "overbought". The stock may be due for a pullback.</li>
      <li><strong>Under 30:</strong> Considered "oversold". Selling exhaustion may be near.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For fundamental investors, an RSI below 30 is an excellent screening tool. It highlights solid companies that the market has indiscriminately dumped during a panic. It is not a buy signal on its own, but an invitation to investigate the fundamentals.</p>

    <h2>What Does NOT Work (Be Honest)</h2>
    <p>Much of traditional technical analysis is akin to financial astrology. As a fundamental investor, you should actively ignore the following:</p>
    <div class="callout callout-negative">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Complex Chart Patterns:</strong> "Head and Shoulders," "Cup and Handle," or "Pennants." These are highly subjective and prone to confirmation bias. You will see whatever pattern justifies your existing bias.</li>
        <li><strong>Fibonacci Retracements:</strong> The idea that markets retrace exactly 61.8% of a move based on a mathematical sequence found in nature has zero robust empirical backing in modern, algorithm-driven equity markets.</li>
        <li><strong>Elliott Wave Theory:</strong> A system so complex and subjective that any failed prediction can be explained away as a "miscount" of the waves.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>The Practical Framework</h2>
    <p>To integrate technicals without losing your fundamental soul, follow this simple sequence:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>The "What" (Fundamentals):</strong> Screen for high ROIC, strong free cash flow, and reasonable valuations. Build your watchlist.</li>
      <li><strong>The "When" (Technicals):</strong> Monitor that watchlist. Wait for the stock to approach a major support level or watch for the RSI to dip into oversold territory (below 30).</li>
      <li><strong>The "Confirmation" (Volume/Trend):</strong> Ensure you aren't fighting a massive institutional exit (high volume sell-off) and prefer to buy when the stock is at least stabilizing relative to its 50-day moving average.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Should fundamental investors use technical analysis?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes, but strictly as a secondary tool. Fundamental analysis should dictate WHAT to buy and sell, while simple technical analysis (like volume and key moving averages) can help optimize WHEN to enter or exit positions.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do support and resistance levels actually work?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes, support and resistance work primarily because of market psychology and memory. They represent price points where large pools of buyers or sellers have historically stepped in, creating self-fulfilling prophecies.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between the 50-day and 200-day moving average?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The 50-day moving average measures the medium-term trend and is closely watched by institutional traders. The 200-day moving average represents the long-term macroeconomic trend; stocks trading below it are generally considered to be in a downtrend.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is RSI a good indicator for value investing?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The Relative Strength Index (RSI) can be useful for value investors when looking to initiate a position in a stock they already like fundamentally. An RSI below 30 indicates the stock is temporarily oversold and might offer a better entry price.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do chart patterns like head and shoulders work?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Most complex chart patterns lack robust statistical evidence. For fundamental investors, relying on subjective patterns like "head and shoulders" or Elliott Wave theory is generally not recommended, as they are prone to confirmation bias.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
